        "created_at": "2025-08-27T17:03:56.435Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Hey Signal community,</p>\n<p>I‚Äôve been using ‚ÄúNote to Self‚Äù a lot for quick notes, and it got me thinking about how cool it would be to have a simple local API in the Signal Desktop app to interact with it programmatically. Basically, just a localhost endpoint (no server-side stuff) that lets you send messages to your own ‚ÄúNote to Self‚Äù thread, set expiration times, delete them, and manage API keys locally for security.</p>\n<p>The main idea is to enable stuff like a ‚Äúsecure clipboard‚Äù ‚Äì imagine a companion app on your desktop that hooks into copy/paste actions and sends the content straight to ‚ÄúNote to Self‚Äù via this API. That way, your clipboard data is encrypted and synced across devices without relying on the OS clipboard, which isn‚Äôt always secure. It could prefix API-sent messages (e.g., ‚Äú[API: AppName] Copied: [content]‚Äù) and log actions locally for tracking.</p>\n<p>Keep it super simple: generate/reset/delete keys in-app, optional expiration on sends (default to thread settings), and deletion by message ID. No remote access, just local for privacy.</p>\n<p>What do you all think? Would love to hear if others have use cases or tweaks!</p>\n<p>Thanks!</p>",
